When spirit commands, fire obeys; fire follows the lead of spirit and fights under its direction‚ as the poet says 216, 217.

That the earth is not solid, but full of cavities giving free room for the movement of air and wind, is a point much insisted on by the poet of Aetna.

96 Non totum ex solido est, ducit namque onmis hiatum, Secta est omnis humus, penitusque cauata latebris Exiles suspensa uias agit.

He compares it, from this point of view, with the body through which the blood passes to and fro along the veins, and again with a heap of stones casually accumulated‚ the interstices in which correspond to the craeks and pores in the earth's fabric.
